{"key":"post-8843736","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8843736</id>\n<content>Actually, I use antibiotic agar for germinating spores too.&amp;nbsp; It gives you a head start on any bacteria that might be on your print.&amp;nbsp; Once you have a clean culture, you transfer it to non-antibiotic treated grains and bulk substrates to grow anyway, so it's only in the spore stage for that use.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's also quite valuable for cloning wild mushrooms.&amp;nbsp; There's so much live bacteria in wild mushrooms that even with antibiotic agar, you'll still need to make a series of transfers until you have a clean culture, but it will help somewhat.&amp;nbsp; I've never experienced any reasons not to use it and lots of reasons to.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>8842415</prev>\n<first>8842365</first>\n<last>8843736</last>\n<when>1219974750</when>\n<utime>08/29/08 04:52 AM</utime>\n</post>"}